def is_dst(dt):
    # DST in UK: last Sunday of March to last Sunday of October
    # March: last Sunday is 25-31
    # October: last Sunday is 25-31
    
    year = dt.year
    
    # Last Sunday of March
    march_last_sunday = datetime(year, 3, 31)
    days_from_sunday = (march_last_sunday.weekday() + 1) % 7  # Days to subtract to get Sunday
    # If today is Sunday, days_from_sunday = 0, so last Sunday is 31
    # If today is Monday, days_from_sunday = 1, so last Sunday is 30
    # etc.
    last_sunday_march_day = 31 - days_from_sunday
    
    # Last Sunday of October
    oct_last_sunday = datetime(year, 10, 31)
    days_from_sunday = (oct_last_sunday.weekday() + 1) % 7
    last_sunday_oct_day = 31 - days_from_sunday
    
    dst_start = datetime(year, 3, last_sunday_march_day, tzinfo=timezone.utc)
    dst_end = datetime(year, 10, last_sunday_oct_day, tzinfo=timezone.utc)
    
    return dst_start <= dt < dst_end

Wait, DST usually starts at 1am UTC, not midnight. But for the purpose of checking the hour, it doesn't matter much since we're checking dates, not times.

Actually, the condition in Pine Script is:
is_dst = (month >= 3 and (month == 3 and dayofweek == dayofweek.sunday and dayofmonth >= 25 or month > 3)) and
         (month <= 10 and (month == 10 and dayofweek == dayofweek.sunday and dayofmonth < 25 or month < 10))

This is equivalent to:
- (month > 3) OR (month == 3 AND dayofmonth >= 25 AND dayofweek == sunday)
- AND
- (month < 10) OR (month == 10 AND dayofweek == sunday AND dayofmonth < 25)

So it's from March 25 (if Sunday) or later in March, to October 24 (if Sunday) or earlier in October.

In Python:
from datetime import datetime, timezone

def is_dst(dt):
    year = dt.year
    
    # Find last Sunday of March
    march_31 = datetime(year, 3, 31)
    days_since_sunday = (march_31.weekday() + 1) % 7  # Monday=0, Sunday=6
    last_sunday_march = 31 - days_since_sunday
    
    # Find last Sunday of October
    oct_31 = datetime(year, 10, 31)
    days_since_sunday = (oct_31.weekday() + 1) % 7
    last_sunday_oct = 31 - days_since_sunday
    
    # DST starts at 1am on last Sunday of March
    dst_start = datetime(year, 3, last_sunday_march, 1, 0, tzinfo=timezone.utc)
    # DST ends at 1am on last Sunday of October
    dst_end = datetime(year, 10, last_sunday_oct, 1, 0, tzinfo=timezone.utc)
    
    return dst_start <= dt < dst_end

But since we're just checking the hour, and DST change happens at 1am or 2am depending on country, and our trading windows start at 7am, the exact hour of transition doesn't matter for our purposes (7am is well after the transition).

So I can simplify to just checking the date range:
def is_dst(dt):
    year = dt.year
    
    # Find last Sunday of March
    march_31 = datetime(year, 3, 31)
    days_since_sunday = (march_31.weekday() + 1) % 7
    last_sunday_march = 31 - days_since_sunday
    
    # Find last Sunday of October
    oct_31 = datetime(year, 10, 31)
    days_since_sunday = (oct_31.weekday() + 1) % 7
    last_sunday_oct = 31 - days_since_sunday
    
    dst_start_date = datetime(year, 3, last_sunday_march).date()
    dst_end_date = datetime(year, 10, last_sunday_oct).date()
    
    current_date = dt.date()
    
    return dst_start_date <= current_date < dst_end_date

Actually, looking at the Pine Script condition again:
is_dst = (month >= 3 and (month == 3 and dayofweek == dayofweek.sunday and dayofmonth >= 25 or month > 3)) and        (month <= 10 and (month == 10 and dayofweek == dayofweek.sunday and dayofmonth < 25 or month < 10))

This is confusing. Let me parse it:
- Part 1: `month >= 3 and (month == 3 and dayofweek == dayofweek.sunday and dayofmonth >= 25 or month > 3)`
  - This is true if month > 3, OR (month == 3 AND it's Sunday AND day >= 25)
  - So from March 25 (if Sunday) or April 1 onwards
  
- Part 2: `month <= 10 and (month == 10 and dayofweek == dayofweek.sunday and dayofmonth < 25 or month < 10)`
  - This is true if month < 10, OR (month == 10 AND it's Sunday AND day < 25)
  - So until October 24 (if Sunday) or September 30

- Combined: From March 25 (Sunday) or April to October 24 (Sunday)